SIMPLE: truce
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Truce
<hw>Truce</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>trewes</ets>,
<ets>triwes</ets>, <ets>treowes</ets>, pl. of <ets>trewe</ets> a truce,
properly, pledge of fidelity, truth, AS. <ets>tre⟦oacute⟧w</ets>
fidelity, faith, troth. See <er>True</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A suspension of arms by agreement of the
commanders of opposing forces; a temporary cessation of hostilities, for
negotiation or other purpose; an armistice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, intermission of action, pain, or contest;
temporary cessation; short quiet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where he may likeliest find⟦br⟧
<qex>Truce</qex> to his restless thoughts.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Flag of truce</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a white
flag carried or exhibited by one of the hostile parties, during the
flying of which hostilities are suspended.</cd> -- <col><b>Truce of
God</b></col>, <cd>a suspension of arms promulgated by the church, which
occasionally took place in the Middle Ages, putting a stop to private
hostilities at or within certain periods.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trucebreaker</ent>⟦br⟧
